# Constructs

- Restricted Definition: Constructs that are used by the system and are not modifiable.
- Aliases Definition: Many constructs have Aliases, such as Thoughts, Datasets, and Attributes. Aliases are meant to be arbitrarily-named identifiers for entities. In almost all cases, these entities can have multiple Aliases, where a primary Alias can be set to show up everywhere in the UI, but other Aliases can still be search for and viewed by hovering over the primary Alias.

- Data Definition: Primitive values assigned to the Attribute of a Thought. Data can be of any type, like a file or string (and possibly more types like numbers, but most others will be defined as Constraints). Data of an Attribute must adhere to the Attribute's Constraints.
- Data Groups Definition: A group of multiple Data values. These are simplified representations of what might be called objects, sets, strings, or dictionaries in programming languages. These may be complex to implement and will come later.

- Thoughts Definition: A collection of Data with a primary "Content" Attribute and a secondary "Alias" Attribute (however in the Dataset UI, the Alias appears to the left). Each field is optional in the database but required in the ALTERED app, however if left blank the Thought will reside in the Drafts Dataset. This provides a surface for humans and AI to fully understand the purpose of, and interact with the Thought and it's associated Data. Could be compared to a row in a database. Under the hood, Thoughts will be automatically be indexed by Tags, which are derived with AI from all of the Thought's Attributes. On a primitive level, thoughts are a Restricted Dataset.
- Thought Drafts Definition: A special type of Restricted Dataset where Thoughts go to when they don't conform to the Schemas of their assigned Datasets, or lack sufficient data to adhere to the base Thought (e.g., a file without any Thought content, or a Thought without an Alias). Drafts are excluded from most views and searches (including Datasets they are assigned) unless explicitly included. Drafts can be removed from drafts when all requirements are met, and then the user can remove the thought from drafts from the Raycast action panel.
- Thought Relations Definition: To be defined. Regards how certain thoughts interact with, and depend on other thoughts.

- Datasets Definition: A named group of Thoughts, represented as a Thought. Datasets can be compared to the table of a database, which provide functionality for arbitrary grouping. Each Dataset requires a Schema.
- Dataset Schemas Definition: Dataset Schemas define the Attributes and their Constraints for a Dataset. This is experimental but Schemas may be able to be represented as a Dataset of Thoughts, each defining an Attribute of it's corresponding Dataset.
- Computed Datasets Definition: A Dataset that automatically assumes any Thoughts that adhere to the Schema, rather than adding them manually. Computed Datasets will allow merging and aggregating Thoughts for several purposes, such as sharing. The exact specifications of this are yet to be defined.

- Attributes Definition: Attributes are just columns of Data on a Thought. Attributes are defined in the Dataset Schema. Attributes from different Datasets all exist on the same Thought, but are are only shown in the Datasets they belong to.
- Attribute Constraints Definition: Attributes are essentially sub-types of Data that apply limitations to narrow the type. Think of these like validation rules - they assume an input with autocompletion, and reject/error if the input does not conform. Attributes come as presets that can be customized with parameters.
- Attribute Constraints Examples: Some example constraints for the "Text" type might be "Kebab-Case", "Literal" (enum), "Number" (may be a separate type, but I like the idea of building from strings), or "Number > Precision" with a parameter specifying 2 decimal places.

- Brains Definition: The most top-level collections of Thoughts. An ALTERED Brain could be compared to an organization in a generic SaaS - it is a container for all user-interactive data.
- Switching Brains: When switching Brains, you leave all of your Systems, Thoughts, Preferences, etc behind, with only your Identity remaining (user model) - which is the only thing above the Brain model.
- Application and System Preferences: **ALL** of ALTERED will eventually store it's state in a user-accessible place: the ALTERED brain. This means things that you _don't need to know about_, like app-level preferences and intra-System variables will be stored in this other Brain. This means if you really wanted to, you could version, manipulate, and share ALTERED internal app state from the ALTERED Brain, within the constraints set on the Attributes and Datasets in that brain.
- Brain Interoperability: Since by default, internal app state will exist in a different dedicated brain, we will need to have functionality for referencing and duplicating/moving Thoughts between Brains. For example, this might mean creating a reference to a "General AI Prompt" within the user's Brain, and wiring that up to a preference in the ALTERED Brain. Cross-brain references will have clear markers that indicate a dependency to make the data boundary clear.
- Example Brains: Some examples of Brains and their use cases might be: Riley Barabash (me - everything I care about knowing); ALTERED (state for Systems and internal operations); Anyone (or <SYSTEM_NAME> - a Brain to collect responses from a public System); or External (outside data or references that want to be cross-referenced from within the primary brain, but want to avoid information pollution).

- Operations Definition: Operations are universalized, serializable functions written in code that can perform arbitrary functionality and/or leverage the tooling exposed by the ALTERED SDK. Operations must export schemas for their input and output, define metadata, dependencies, state, and more. The exact specifications for this may change.
- Extensions Definition: Extensions are bundles of code that expose Operations to ALTERED. Think of these like npm packages - except we will make the publishing process easier, and the code will be included in our codebase via GitHub PRs. The shape and process for this is yet to be defined.

- Use Cases for Extensions: The case for Extensions is still subjective. Since our UI, logic, and data will all be serializable, most customization can be done by either (a) building custom Systems/Actions that utilize existing Operations, and/or (b) making an API request to a remote server. If a user doesn't want to host a server or can't achieve certain functionality without code, an Extension (or possibly, a singular custom code or templating syntax block) could be viable.

- Components Definition: Components are the primitive building blocks of the UI. They expose several parameters similar to Operations (yet to be defined).
- Interfaces Definition: Interfaces (comparable to views/screens) are composed of a set of Components that interact with Operations to form stateful and functional user experiences. Interfaces will expose several parameters, such as inputs/outputs as well.
- Interface Flows Definition: A sequence of connected Interfaces that make up an Action.

- Actions Definition: Actions are orchestrations of Interface Flows that create a sufficient platform for a user to achieve a specific objective. These are the main entry points in ALTERED, and show up as commands in Raycast.

- Systems Definition: Sets of Actions with a Guide on to use them and additional metadata for the Marketplace, among other things.
- System Guides Definition: Interactive docs that help users navigate, understand and use a System.

